no.motif.f.alias

Interface LazyVal<V>

  • All Superinterfaces:
    Fn0<V>

    public interface LazyVal<V>
extends Fn0<V>
    A LazyVal can be implemented in place of an Fn0 to communicate that the value yielded from the function is a lazily calculated. This type does not provide anything over Fn0 but being a more specific nominative type, where appropriate, solely for communication purposes.

    Good practice

    One should never accept LazyVals as argument types, but always implement method signatures to accept Fn0.
